            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XVII.R19</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Penitent Pancks&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-ed40cca2-7fff-4202-6576-2c57fb3a4d0f\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The chapter opens with Pancks&rsquo;s &ldquo;remorse&rdquo;; he rushes to find Clennam and, upon witnessing Clennam&rsquo;s agony, &ldquo;tear[s] at his tough hair in a most pitiless and cruel manner&rdquo; (LD 692). The close of chapter 28 in the following number will reinforce this remorse in words that echo this note, describing Pancks as &ldquo;still penitent and depressed&rdquo; (733).&nbsp;</p>"
